    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hollandaise sauce breaks because the egg yolks get too hot and the emulsion collapses, leaving the fat (butter) separate from the water-based yolk mixture. This is often caused by the butter melting too quickly or the pan being too hot. While the sauce is technically ruined and can't be perfectly fixed, you can try a quick rescue by whisking in a splash of hot water or lemon juice to re-emulsify it, though it usually won't be as smooth as a fresh batch. For the best results, start with a cold pan and gently whisk the yolks before adding the butter in small, slow increments.",
      "source": "target",
